urchase-access" aria-controls="core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Get Access" title="Get Access" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="sr-only">Get Access</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-references" aria-controls="core-collateral-references" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="References" title="References" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-references"></i><span class="sr-only">References</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-figures" aria-controls="core-collateral-figures" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Figures" title="Figures" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-photo"></i><span class="sr-only">Figures</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-tables" aria-controls="core-collateral-tables" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Tables" title="Tables" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-table"></i><span class="sr-only">Tables</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-media" aria-controls="core-collateral-media" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Media" title="Media" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-play-circle-filled"></i><span class="sr-only">Media</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-share" aria-controls="core-collateral-share" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Share" title="Share" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-share"></i><span class="sr-only">Share</span></a></li></ul></nav></div></div><div data-core-wrapper="content"><div id="abstracts" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="abstract" property="abstract" typeof="Text" role="doc-abstract"><h2 property="name">Abstract</h2><div role="paragraph">Coronary artery fistulas are anomalous terminations of the coronary arteries. Most often, these fistulas are incidentally identified in the adult and pediatric populations. Many patients are asymptomatic; however, an awareness of these fistulas is important because they have been associated with various clinical features, including chest pain or heart failure in young patients. Correct diagnosis of coronary artery fistulas is important, and early surgical correction is indicated because of the high prevalence of late symptoms and complications. Traditionally, conventional angiography has been used for the diagnosis of coronary anomalies. With more frequent use of 64-row multi-detector computed tomography (CT) in chest and cardiac imaging, the number of incidentally found coronary artery fistulas has been increasing. CT angiography and conventional angiography can have additive value in diagnosis of this cardiac anomaly. In every CT study of the heart, special attention should be paid to the courses and terminations of the coronary arteries to detect these potentially fatal anomalies.</div><div role="paragraph">© RSNA, 2009</div></section></div></div><section id="bodymatter" data-extent="bodymatter" property="articleBody" typeof="Text"><div class="core-container"><section aria-labelledby="denial-block-title" class="denial-block "><h2 id="denial-block-title" class="denial-block__title">Get full access to this article</h2><p class="denial-block__text">View all available purchase options and get full access to this article.</p><div class="denial-block__cta"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span>Get Access</span></a></div><footer class="denial-block__footer"><span>Already a Subscriber? </span><span>Sign in as an </span><a href="/action/showLogin?redirectUri=/doi/10.1148/rg.293085120">individual</a><span> or via your </span><a href="/action/ssostart?uri=/doi/10.1148/rg.293085120">institution</a></footer></section></div></section><section id="backmatter" data-extent="backmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="core-sec-figures" data-type="figures"><h2>Figures</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F1A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085120/asset/images/g09ma21g01a.jpeg" height="1419" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F1A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 1a.</b>  CAF draining into the right ventricle in a 7-year-old boy with dyspnea. Coronal oblique maximum intensity projection (MIP) image <b>(a)</b> and volume-rendered images <b>(b–e)</b> from computed tomography (CT) show an ectatic proximal RCA (arrow in <b>a–c</b>) with a distal saccular aneurysmal dilatation (arrowhead) along the anteroinferior surface of the right ventricle.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085120&amp;id=F1A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F1B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085120/asset/images/g09ma21c01b.jpeg" height="1198" width="1280" aria-labelledby="F1B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 1b.</b>  CAF draining into the right ventricle in a 7-year-old boy with dyspnea. Coronal oblique maximum intensity projection (MIP) image <b>(a)</b> and volume-rendered images <b>(b–e)</b> from computed tomography (CT) show an ectatic proximal RCA (arrow in <b>a–c</b>) with a distal saccular aneurysmal dilatation (arrowhead) along the anteroinferior surface of the right ventricle.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085120&amp;id=F1B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F1C" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085120/asset/images/g09ma21c01c.jpeg" height="1280" width="1173" aria-labelledby="F1C" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 1c.</b>  CAF draining into the right ventricle in a 7-year-old boy with dyspnea. Coronal oblique maximum intensity projection (MIP) image <b>(a)</b> and volume-rendered images <b>(b–e)</b> from computed tomography (CT) show an ectatic proximal RCA (arrow in <b>a–c</b>) with a distal saccular aneurysmal dilatation (arrowhead) along the anteroinferior surface of the right ventricle.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085120&amp;id=F1C">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F1D" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085120/asset/images/g09ma21g01d.jpeg" height="1465" width="1512" aria-labelledby="F1D" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 1d.</b>  CAF draining into the right ventricle in a 7-year-old boy with dyspnea. Coronal oblique maximum intensity projection (MIP) image <b>(a)</b> and volume-rendered images <b>(b–e)</b> from computed tomography (CT) show an ectatic proximal RCA (arrow in <b>a–c</b>) with a distal saccular aneurysmal dilatation (arrowhead) along the anteroinferior surface of the right ventricle.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085120&amp;id=F1D">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F1E" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085120/asset/images/g09ma21c01e.jpeg" height="1280" width="967" aria-labelledby="F1E" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 1e.</b>  CAF draining into the right ventricle in a 7-year-old boy with dyspnea. Coronal oblique maximum intensity projection (MIP) image <b>(a)</b> and volume-rendered images <b>(b–e)</b> from computed tomography (CT) show an ectatic proximal RCA (arrow in <b>a–c</b>) with a distal saccular aneurysmal dilatation (arrowhead) along the anteroinferior surface of the right ventricle.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085120&amp;id=F1E">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F2A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085120/asset/images/g09ma21g02a.jpeg" height="1800" width="1725" aria-labelledby="F2A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 2a.</b>  Treated CAF in a 17-year-old boy in whom an LCA-to–right ventricle fistula was diagnosed in infancy. At the age of 9 years, he underwent coil embolization. <b>(a–d)</b> Axial <b>(a–c)</b> and coronal reformatted <b>(d)</b> CT images show aneurysmal dilatation of the proximal LCA (arrow in <b>a</b>) and multiple embolization coils in the distal LCA (arrow in <b>b–d</b>). <b>(e)</b> Image from conventional angiography shows successful occlusion of the fistula with coil embolization (arrowhead).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085120&amp;id=F2A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F2B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085120/asset/images/g09ma21g02b.jpeg" height="1800" width="1686" aria-labelledby="F2B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 2b.</b>  Treated CAF in a 17-year-old boy in whom an LCA-to–right ventricle fistula was diagnosed in infancy. At the age of 9 years, he underwent coil embolization. <b>(a–d)</b> Axial <b>(a–c)</b> and coronal reformatted <b>(d)</b> CT images show aneurysmal dilatation of the proximal LCA (arrow in <b>a</b>) and multiple embolization coils in the distal LCA (arrow in <b>b–d</b>). <b>(e)</b> Image from conventional angiography shows successful occlusion of the fistula with coil embolization (arrowhead).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085120&amp;id=F2B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F2C" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085120/asset/images/g09ma21g02c.jpeg" height="1717" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F2C" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 2c.</b>  Treated CAF in a 17-year-old boy in whom an LCA-to–right ventricle fistula was diagnosed in infancy. At the age of 9 years, he underwent coil embolization. <b>(a–d)</b> Axial <b>(a–c)</b> and coronal reformatted <b>(d)</b> CT images show aneurysmal dilatation of the proximal LCA (arrow in <b>a</b>) and multiple embolization coils in the distal LCA (arrow in <b>b–d</b>). <b>(e)</b> Image from conventional angiography shows successful occlusion of the fistula with coil embolization (arrowhead).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085120&amp;id=F2C">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F2D" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085120/asset/images/g09ma21g02d.jpeg" height="1800" width="1794" aria-labelledby="F2D" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 2d.</b>  Treated CAF in a 17-year-old boy in whom an LCA-to–right ventricle fistula was diagnosed in infancy. At the age of 9 years, he underwent coil embolization. <b>(a–d)</b> Axial <b>(a–c)</b> and coronal reformatted <b>(d)</b> CT images show aneurysmal dilatation of the proximal LCA (arrow in <b>a</b>) and multiple embolization coils in the distal LCA (arrow in <b>b–d</b>). <b>(e)</b> Image from conventional angiography shows successful occlusion of the fistula with coil embolization (arrowhead).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085120&amp;id=F2D">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F2E" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085120/asset/images/g09ma21g02e.jpeg" height="1800" width="1656" aria-labelledby="F2E" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 2e.</b>  Treated CAF in a 17-year-old boy in whom an LCA-to–right ventricle fistula was diagnosed in infancy. At the age of 9 years, he underwent coil embolization. <b>(a–d)</b> Axial <b>(a–c)</b> and coronal reformatted <b>(d)</b> CT images show aneurysmal dilatation of the proximal LCA (arrow in <b>a</b>) and multiple embolization coils in the distal LCA (arrow in <b>b–d</b>). <b>(e)</b> Image from conventional angiography shows successful occlusion of the fistula with coil embolization (arrowhead).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085120&amp;id=F2E">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F3A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085120/asset/images/g09ma21g03a.jpeg" height="1593" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F3A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 3a.</b>  CAF draining into the right atrium in a 54-year-old man with shortness of breath. <b>(a–c)</b> Coronal oblique MIP <b>(a, b)</b> and axial <b>(c)</b> CT images show the LCA to be aneurysmal (arrow) with flecks of calcification. <b>(d–f)</b> Angiograms show the dilated, tortuous fistula (arrow in <b>d</b> and <b>e</b>) extending from the LCA to the right atrium (arrowhead in <b>f</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085120&amp;id=F3A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F3B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085120/asset/images/g09ma21g03b.jpeg" height="1595" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F3B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 3b.</b>  CAF draining into the right atrium in a 54-year-old man with shortness of breath. <b>(a–c)</b> Coronal oblique MIP <b>(a, b)</b> and axial <b>(c)</b> CT images show the LCA to be aneurysmal (arrow) with flecks of calcification. <b>(d–f)</b> Angiograms show the dilated, tortuous fistula (arrow in <b>d</b> and <b>e</b>) extending from the LCA to the right atrium (arrowhead in <b>f</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085120&amp;id=F3B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F3C" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085120/asset/images/g09ma21g03c.jpeg" height="1516" width="1638" aria-labelledby="F3C" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 3c.</b>  CAF draining into the right atrium in a 54-year-old man with shortness of breath. <b>(a–c)</b> Coronal oblique MIP <b>(a, b)</b> and axial <b>(c)</b> CT images show the LCA to be aneurysmal (arrow) with flecks of calcification. <b>(d–f)</b> Angiograms show the dilated, tortuous fistula (arrow in <b>d</b> and <b>e</b>) extending from the LCA to the right atrium (arrowhead in <b>f</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085120&amp;id=F3C">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F3D" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085120/asset/images/g09ma21g03d.jpeg" height="1680" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F3D" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 3d.</b>  CAF draining into the right atrium in a 54-year-old man with shortness of breath. <b>(a–c)</b> Coronal oblique MIP <b>(a, b)</b> and axial <b>(c)</b> CT images show the LCA to be aneurysmal (arrow) with flecks of calcification. <b>(d–f)</b> Angiograms show the dilated, tortuous fistula (arrow in <b>d</b> and <b>e</b>) extending from the LCA to the right atrium (arrowhead in <b>f</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085120&amp;id=F3D">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F3E" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085120/asset/images/g09ma21g03e.jpeg" height="1756" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F3E" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 3e.</b>  CAF draining into the right atrium in a 54-year-old man with shortness of breath. <b>(a–c)</b> Coronal oblique MIP <b>(a, b)</b> and axial <b>(c)</b> CT images show the LCA to be aneurysmal (arrow) with flecks of calcification. <b>(d–f)</b> Angiograms show the dilated, tortuous fistula (arrow in <b>d</b> and <b>e</b>) extending from the LCA to the right atrium (arrowhead in <b>f</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085120&amp;id=F3E">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F3F" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085120/asset/images/g09ma21g03f.jpeg" height="1775" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F3F" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 3f.</b>  CAF draining into the right atrium in a 54-year-old man with shortness of breath. <b>(a–c)</b> Coronal oblique MIP <b>(a, b)</b> and axial <b>(c)</b> CT images show the LCA to be aneurysmal (arrow) with flecks of calcification. <b>(d–f)</b> Angiograms show the dilated, tortuous fistula (arrow in <b>d</b> and <b>e</b>) extending from the LCA to the right atrium (arrowhead in <b>f</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085120&amp;id=F3F">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F4A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085120/asset/images/g09ma21g04a.jpeg" height="1638" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F4A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 4a.</b>  CAF draining into the pulmonary artery in a 78-year-old woman with chest pain in whom an anomalous vessel was noted during cardiac catheterization. CT was performed to further define the abnormal vessel. <b>(a, b)</b> Sagittal MIP <b>(a)</b> and axial <b>(b)</b> CT images show a fistula (arrowhead in <b>a</b>) from a large branch of the RCA (arrow in <b>a</b>) to the main pulmonary artery <i>(MPA)</i> above the level of the valve. There is an aneurysm in the proximal portion of the fistula. <b>(c)</b> Endoluminal view shows the insertion of the fistula (arrowhead) into the MPA.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085120&amp;id=F4A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F4B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085120/asset/images/g09ma21g04b.jpeg" height="1599" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F4B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 4b.</b>  CAF draining into the pulmonary artery in a 78-year-old woman with chest pain in whom an anomalous vessel was noted during cardiac catheterization. CT was performed to further define the abnormal vessel. <b>(a, b)</b> Sagittal MIP <b>(a)</b> and axial <b>(b)</b> CT images show a fistula (arrowhead in <b>a</b>) from a large branch of the RCA (arrow in <b>a</b>) to the main pulmonary artery <i>(MPA)</i> above the level of the valve. There is an aneurysm in the proximal portion of the fistula. <b>(c)</b> Endoluminal view shows the insertion of the fistula (arrowhead) into the MPA.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085120&amp;id=F4B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F4C" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085120/asset/images/g09ma21c04c.jpeg" height="1152" width="1280" aria-labelledby="F4C" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 4c.</b>  CAF draining into the pulmonary artery in a 78-year-old woman with chest pain in whom an anomalous vessel was noted during cardiac catheterization. CT was performed to further define the abnormal vessel. <b>(a, b)</b> Sagittal MIP <b>(a)</b> and axial <b>(b)</b> CT images show a fistula (arrowhead in <b>a</b>) from a large branch of the RCA (arrow in <b>a</b>) to the main pulmonary artery <i>(MPA)</i> above the level of the valve. There is an aneurysm in the proximal portion of the fistula. <b>(c)</b> Endoluminal view shows the insertion of the fistula (arrowhead) into the MPA.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085120&amp;id=F4C">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F5A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085120/asset/images/g09ma21g05a.jpeg" height="1595" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F5A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 5a.</b>  CAF draining into the pulmonary artery in a 74-year-old man with chest pain in whom an anomalous vessel was seen at coronary angiography. Axial MIP <b>(a, b)</b> and coronal <b>(c)</b> CT images show an aneurysmal fistula (arrows) from the left anterior descending artery (<i>LAD</i> in <b>a</b>) to the pulmonary artery (<i>PA</i> in <b>b</b>). The tortuous vessel encases the MPA and enters this artery on the right side (arrowhead in <b>b</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085120&amp;id=F5A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F5B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085120/asset/images/g09ma21g05b.jpeg" height="1541" width="1728" aria-labelledby="F5B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 5b.</b>  CAF draining into the pulmonary artery in a 74-year-old man with chest pain in whom an anomalous vessel was seen at coronary angiography. Axial MIP <b>(a, b)</b> and coronal <b>(c)</b> CT images show an aneurysmal fistula (arrows) from the left anterior descending artery (<i>LAD</i> in <b>a</b>) to the pulmonary artery (<i>PA</i> in <b>b</b>). The tortuous vessel encases the MPA and enters this artery on the right side (arrowhead in <b>b</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085120&amp;id=F5B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F5C" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085120/asset/images/g09ma21g05c.jpeg" height="1637" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F5C" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 5c.</b>  CAF draining into the pulmonary artery in a 74-year-old man with chest pain in whom an anomalous vessel was seen at coronary angiography. Axial MIP <b>(a, b)</b> and coronal <b>(c)</b> CT images show an aneurysmal fistula (arrows) from the left anterior descending artery (<i>LAD</i> in <b>a</b>) to the pulmonary artery (<i>PA</i> in <b>b</b>). The tortuous vessel encases the MPA and enters this artery on the right side (arrowhead in <b>b</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085120&amp;id=F5C">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F6A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085120/asset/images/g09ma21c06a.jpeg" height="1171" width="1280" aria-labelledby="F6A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 6a.</b>  CAF draining into the pulmonary artery in a 50-year-old man with atypical chest pain. Volume-rendered <b>(a, b)</b> and axial MIP <b>(c)</b> CT images show a tortuous vessel (arrows) arising from the RCA. The tortuous vessel passes anterior to the pulmonary artery (<i>PA</i> in <b>c</b>) and forms a network before it enters the MPA (arrowhead in <b>b</b> and <b>c</b>) just distal to the valve. Cardiac catheterization showed only a vessel from the RCA to a pericardiac structure.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085120&amp;id=F6A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F6B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085120/asset/images/g09ma21c06b.jpeg" height="1161" width="1280" aria-labelledby="F6B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 6b.</b>  CAF draining into the pulmonary artery in a 50-year-old man with atypical chest pain. Volume-rendered <b>(a, b)</b> and axial MIP <b>(c)</b> CT images show a tortuous vessel (arrows) arising from the RCA. The tortuous vessel passes anterior to the pulmonary artery (<i>PA</i> in <b>c</b>) and forms a network before it enters the MPA (arrowhead in <b>b</b> and <b>c</b>) just distal to the valve. Cardiac catheterization showed only a vessel from the RCA to a pericardiac structure.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085120&amp;id=F6B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F6C" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085120/asset/images/g09ma21g06c.jpeg" height="1788" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F6C" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 6c.</b>  CAF draining into the pulmonary artery in a 50-year-old man with atypical chest pain. Volume-rendered <b>(a, b)</b> and axial MIP <b>(c)</b> CT images show a tortuous vessel (arrows) arising from the RCA. The tortuous vessel passes anterior to the pulmonary artery (<i>PA</i> in <b>c</b>) and forms a network before it enters the MPA (arrowhead in <b>b</b> and <b>c</b>) just distal to the valve. Cardiac catheterization showed only a vessel from the RCA to a pericardiac structure.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085120&amp;id=F6C">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F7A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085120/asset/images/g09ma21g07a.jpeg" height="1648" width="1656" aria-labelledby="F7A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 7a.</b>  CAF draining into the coronary sinus in a 66-year-old man with dilated cardiomyopathy. <b>(a–g)</b> Axial MIP <b>(a–d)</b> (displayed from superior <b>[a]</b> to inferior <b>[d]</b>), coronal oblique MIP <b>(e)</b>, and volume-rendered <b>(f, g)</b> CT images show a tortuous and elongated RCA with a fistulous communication (arrow in <b>a–c</b> and <b>e–g</b>) to the coronary sinus (arrow in <b>d</b>). <b>(h–j)</b> Angiographic images show the fistulous connection between the RCA (arrow in <b>h</b> and <b>i</b>) and the coronary sinus (arrow in <b>j</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085120&amp;id=F7A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F7B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085120/asset/images/g09ma21g07b.jpeg" height="1692" width="1665" aria-labelledby="F7B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 7b.</b>  CAF draining into the coronary sinus in a 66-year-old man with dilated cardiomyopathy. <b>(a–g)</b> Axial MIP <b>(a–d)</b> 